description.text:
A version 1.0 of a screen case for a 7" screen. It is intended to be mounted onto a printer frame and connected to a Raspberry Pi 3 for use as an "on-printer" computer.

The screen will require:
4 M3/M4 5mm screws and nuts for the screen mounting.
4 M3/M4 12mm screws and nuts for the face cover mounting.
4 M3/M4 12mm screws and nuts for the back-plate mounting.
A backplate (I used a small sheet of 2 mm aluminum cut to size and drilled holes for mounting).

For version 2.0,
-the screen width was either incorrect or the print was inaccurate. Decrease width of left vertical bar on faceplate.
-the faceplate-body connectors need to be thinner to allow screen more room.
-the screen mounting spaces need to be as thin as the faceplate-body connectors.
-alter the HDMI and USB hole port for correct spacing.
-adjust nut-trap sizes. These were either slightly too small or the print was inaccurate.
-increase wall thickness by 0.5-1.0 mm to increase strength.

description.text:
This Thing is a clip for hanging a wire antenna along the fascia (and bargeboard) at the edge of your roof. It is designed to hold a 3mm max diameter wire. I recommend only using this for receiving HF/MF radio signals, While it is totally possible to use these parts to make a 450 ohm ladder line fed doublet/dipole, transmitting on this wire held only 16 mm away from your wooden fascia board is entirely up to you. I officially do not recommend transmitting using these parts.

I have also included an "adapter/junction/tie point" for hooking it up to 450 ohm ladder line, tilted at 25³. It is not a balun, since I am going from doublet/dipole (balanced) to 450 ohm ladder line (balanced), and doing no transformation.

When not in use, and when lightening/thunderstorms are about, DISCONNECT THE ANTENNA FROM YOUR EQUIPMENT! Then secure the end of the antenna away from your house. As with all antennas, it will become a lightning rod, destroying all in its path if it is struck. You have been warned. Be safe. Take no chances.

The Things include a hole to use for nailing it into place, with a .5 mm "shell" across the top of the hole. This is so you can pre-load your nail into the hole, and the shell should should hold the nail in place until you have positioned the clip, and can swing a hammer.

The wire slot entry point is angled with respect to the final wire position. As long as the wire is aligned with the fascia board, it will not pop out.

...I'm hoping that this wire will be stealth enough to avoid the notice of the HOA. It sure would be nice to work 80 meters...

I'll be uploading pictures of it in place, once I get up on the roof (with two ~60-foot lengths of disassembled cat5 conductors and a length of 450 ohm ladder line). Note: there is no coax balun in this design. I have an MFJ-971 tuner which handles balanced line for me. So the only coax in this system will be the 18" LM400 between the tuner and my Icom. Wish me luck!

Arrow storage clips that keep fletchings protected.
I keep my arrows in my soft bow case and I was bothered that my fletchings were always getting crushed in their quiver. These clips protect the fletchings and keep the arrows packed nice and dense. The clips can be stacked and clipped together so one set doesn't squash another.
The clips can be quickly removed with a 90 degree turn.
To put the arrows in I recommend installing a clip on one end, then inserting the other clip between all 6 arrows at the other end and twisting it 90 degrees into place before snapping the arrows in. Then be sure to twist all the arrows into alignment so the fletchings aren’t getting bent by other arrows or other fletchings.
These are a nice tight fit on my carbon arrows with 7.53mm OD, but you can easily scale them up or down for whatever the OD of your arrows are.

Enjoy!

title: Arduino Mega 2560 and Due adapter plate for Prusa i3 Improved laser cut frame + VIDEO

description.text:
Basically the holes on the left wing of the Prusa i3 Improved for laser cut do not match up with the Arduino Mega 2560 and Arduino Due.

Right now I only use the upper most right hole to mount my Arduino Due and RAMPS-FD shield.

I took measurement on my own frame and from the .DXF file of the frame and they match up. Then I found the measurements on a blog for the holes of the Arduino Mega / Due.

In Fusion 360 I made a sketch of the hole locations and drew lines around them to make a body. Afterwards I decided to save on print time and filament by splitting the body into upper and lower mounts.

You are free too download and modify. Get the source from Autodesk Gallery.

Using Netfabb Standard I checked the STL files for problems. Glad to say there aren't any. :)

Requires M3 hardware (7 bolts, 7 nuts and washers), preferably stainless steel, otherwise it should be fine too.

Subcribe to my youtube. You can see this thing getting printed here.with a little bit of a Fusion 360 peek ;).

title: Double 40mm fan mount for Buddaschnozle on a Greg Wade extruder.

description.text:
This is the solution I found so far to integrate both layer and fuser fans. Internal ducts drive air independently to the peek of the Budda and to the layer being printed, so you can software-drive the layer fan as you need it. The rounded triangular shape fits tightly to the buddas body so no air should be going downwards, and it escapes after warming up through the bubbled pattern. The layer fan duct, on the left, blows down through the left port and also in a certain amount to the right port, through a small tube that connects both of them. The present design is slightly improved from the one I finally printed for me, but not tested, though as far as I know there are no major flaws in it. If any mistake should arise, please let me know and I will fix it asap.
The four parts get linked together by the means of 8 M3x15 screws with captive nuts, that may be a bit tricky to locate in their places, but that was one of the things I tried to correct in this final design and I hope they are ok now.

description.text:
Same exact shape as the original strong flat hinge design, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1905532, but sliced so you can have two colors! Also makes it easier to print, in case you've had problems with the original "all in one" print being fused together.

Just print out the attached file twice, in two different colors. Each cubie is composed of two identically shaped pieces. When completed you'll end up with four identical cubies, and four mirror image cubies (with eight connecting pieces).

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1d98TyMcjIP

It's easiest to sand the "inside" of the pieces now. 240 grit works well (this also helps to roughen up the pieces for gluing).

After printing, acetone works great for gluing the pieces together (just use a q-tip and brush onto both sides that are to be attached). Glue all the cubies together, then arrange them in the correct order. I stacked them in a 2x2 cube with all the same color facing outwards (pay attention to the hinge orientation!)

Then add all the hinges so you end up with four pairs of 2x1 pieces (pay attention to the hinge colors!) Then add the hinges so you end up with two 2x2 pieces. Finish off by adding the last two hinges.

All the pieces printed! Assembled! Connected, vertically! Connected on the bottom! Finished off with the top connections!
